This is caused by your GO statements, they represent a new query batch, so variables don&#39;t carry over after a GO. However you are altering a view, which is required by SQL to be the first statement of a Batch, so removing the GOs won&#39;t work in your case.

What I would suggest doing is something like this

    create view test as select 1 a
    
    select * from test
    
    declare @a int = 2;
    declare @sql_statement nvarchar(250) =&#39;alter view test as select &#39;+CAST(@a as nvarchar)+&#39; as a&#39;;
    EXECUTE sp_executesql @sql_statement;

You can build your Alter view statment like a string and then execute it with the stored procedure &quot;sp_executesql&quot;, this way you don&#39;t need a GO to execute the Alter View.

------
Edit: Be extremely careful with what you drop onto sp_executesql, it&#39;s really easy to cause SQL Injection if you use it carelessly.

